      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver passes standard benchmark cases (lid-driven cavity, Poiseuille flow) to within 1% of analytical solution.",
      "rationale": "OpenFOAM v9 was verified against the lid-driven cavity benchmark at Re=100 and Re=1000, and against Poiseuille flow. Maximum deviation from analytical solution is 0.4%. Code verification for the neural network training routine is satisfied by gradient-check tests confirming correct backpropagation implementation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for predicted RH at all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed on the baseline pump geometry (coarse: 1.2M cells, medium: 3.8M cells, fine: 11.4M cells). GCI values for RH ranged from 1.8% to 3.9% across operating points, all below the 5% threshold. The medium mesh (3.8M cells) was selected for training data generation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, pump speed, flow rate) match simulation boundary conditions within stated uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "Bench test fluid (bovine blood, hematocrit 33±2%) properties were measured and applied as CFD inlet conditions. Pump rotational speed was controlled to ±15 RPM; flow rate to ±0.05 L/min. Temperature was maintained at 37±0.5°C throughout. All boundary conditions are within the stated uncertainty envelope of the experimental measurements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Surrogate-predicted RH agrees with experimental RH within 10% at all 5 operating points.",
      "rationale": "Surrogate predictions deviate from experimental RH measurements by 1.2% to 4.7% across the 5 operating points, well within the 10% acceptance criterion. The worst-case operating point is correctly identified by the surrogate. Note: these comparisons are based on the single trained surrogate instance; seed-to-seed variability in predictions was not formally assessed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion and clinical endpoint.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is the primary regulatory QoI for Class II CPB devices per FDA guidance. The surrogate is trained and evaluated exclusively on RH predictions. The acceptance criterion RH < 1 directly corresponds to the predicate device comparison required by the regulatory pathway."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments use the same pump geometry, operating range, and fluid as the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry under the same 5 flow-speed operating points defined in the COU. Bovine blood at physiological hematocrit was used, consistent with ASTM F1841 hemolysis testing standards. The validation domain is directly representative of the intended COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence of CFD residuals to below 1e-5 for all equations.",
      "rationale": "Not assessed at MRL 2 for this factor. Iterative convergence was monitored during training data generation and all runs achieved residuals below 1e-4; formal quantification of solver error contribution to total numerical uncertainty is deferred per MRL 2 scoping."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented user qualification and simulation execution checklist.",
      "rationale": "Not assessed at MRL 2. Simulation analysts hold graduate-level CFD training and completed internal competency review. Formal use-error quantification is not required at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis power-law sub-model are justified for the flow regime and validated against published data.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model is applied; prior literature demonstrates its suitability for rotating blood-contacting devices at the Reynolds numbers encountered (Re 2,000–18,000). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is used as the damage accumulation sub-model, consistent with FDA-recognized practice for CFD hemolysis assessment. Neural network architecture (feedforward, 3 hidden layers) was selected based on cross-validation performance on a development split."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity analysis identifies dominant input parameters; uncertainty in key inputs is bounded.",
      "rationale": "A one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis across 8 geometric and operating parameters identified impeller clearance gap and rotational speed as the dominant inputs affecting RH (combined sensitivity index > 0.65). Blood viscosity uncertainty (±8%) propagates to RH uncertainty of ±3.1%. Inlet flow rate uncertainty (±0.05 L/min) contributes ±1.8% to RH. These are within acceptable bounds for MRL 2."
    },
